package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: adler2
  version: 2.0.1
  revision: 89a031a0f42eeff31c70dc598b398cbf31f1680f
  digest: xAuHDrz_SkzqnoJ6i6czhhdqKAADsTUBlNcl1EA_n5I
review:
  thoroughness: high
  understanding: high
  rating: strong
comment: |-
  Small (~440 LoC) clean-room Adler-32 checksum implementation, the
  community-maintained fork of jonas-schievink/adler after the
  original was archived in 2024. The crate is depended on transitively
  by miniz_oxide/flate2 and (via `rustc-dep-of-std`) by libstd's
  panic backtrace code, so it has had wide exposure.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): `build = false` in Cargo.toml
  (no build.rs), no proc-macro, no `include_bytes!`, no
  Command/syscalls, no network, no obfuscation. Zero runtime deps;
  the only declared dependency is an optional
  `rustc-std-workspace-core` (gated on the `rustc-dep-of-std`
  feature, only enabled when built as part of libstd). License is
  permissive (0BSD OR MIT OR Apache-2.0), repository link is valid,
  authors are plausible (oyvindln is a long-time miniz_oxide
  contributor).
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): N/A - `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]` at
  src/lib.rs:16, and grep across the crate confirms zero `unsafe`
  occurrences outside that forbid line and a doc bullet.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): N/A - no unsafe code to check.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): Walked the algorithm in src/algo.rs. The
  chunked SIMD-friendly implementation processes 4 bytes at a time
  with CHUNK_SIZE = 5552*4 = 22208 bytes between modulus reductions.
  Bounds: a, b are kept < MOD (65521) between calls; inside a chunk
  the worst-case growth of b is CHUNK_SIZE*MOD = ~1.45e9, comfortably
  below 2^32. The `b += CHUNK_SIZE as u32 * a` at algo.rs:72 and the
  `b_vec.0[3] += (MOD - a_vec.0[3]) * 3` finalization at algo.rs:92
  both stay in range. Public API surface is minimal. The BufRead
  loop in lib.rs:206 correctly terminates on empty buffer and bubbles
  read errors. Tests cover empty, zeros, ones, mixed, the Wikipedia
  reference vector, resume via `from_checksum`, and BufRead refill
  paths. No off-by-one, overflow, or panic-on-input issues found.
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project
  rules.
