comment: |-
  Read every .rs file under src/, plus Cargo.toml, build.rs, README, and
  the GitHub Actions CI workflow. Authored by dtolnay; widely used.
  
  build.rs (concern #1): only rustc version probing and feature
  detection. compile_probe runs rustc against src/nightly.rs in a
  scratch subdir of OUT_DIR (created and then removed) to detect the
  unstable error_generic_member_access feature. No network access,
  no writes outside OUT_DIR, no shelling out beyond rustc. Output is
  restricted to cargo:rustc-cfg / rustc-check-cfg println directives.
  process::exit(1) is reached only on its own cleanup or env failures.
  
  unsafe (concerns #2 and #3): 121 `unsafe` occurrences across 7 files.
  The crate uses a manual thin-pointer vtable for `Error` (src/error.rs,
  src/ptr.rs) so anyhow::Error is one word wide. Every unsafe fn and
  unsafe block I read has a preceding `// Safety:` comment naming the
  invariant ("requires layout of *e to match ErrorImpl<E>",
  "MessageError is repr(transparent) so it is okay to cast…", "passing
  vtable that operates on the right type", etc.). The pattern is
  internally consistent: each vtable is built alongside the typed
  ErrorImpl<E> and cast targets match. repr(C) on ErrorImpl /
  ContextError pins field order so the vtable lookup at error.rs:1068
  is sound. ensure.rs::Buf uses str::from_utf8_unchecked on bytes it
  just wrote via a fmt::Write that only accepts &str — sound.
  CI runs `cargo miri test` with MIRIFLAGS=-Zmiri-strict-provenance
  (.github/workflows/ci.yml lines 124-136), so the vtable / pointer
  arithmetic is exercised under miri. No cap applied.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): no bugs found. The downcast machinery
  uses ManuallyDrop carefully to avoid double-drops; the
  context_chain_drop_rest recursion at error.rs:1016 correctly
  forwards the target TypeId down the chain.
  
  Cargo.toml: dual MIT/Apache-2.0, repository link present, version
  matches crate contents, only optional dep is `backtrace`.
