package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: arrayref
  version: 0.3.9
  revision: f8d0299d863922db6c409d08098941e833b70d69
  digest: ajObBdoQl0EITpwV4ZqwGhF3cJFVspfmhNyVrhwhaCE
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: neutral
comment: |-
  Tiny `no_std` crate: a single `src/lib.rs` (~500 lines) exposing four
  declarative macros (`array_ref!`, `array_refs!`, `mut_array_refs!`,
  `array_mut_ref!`) that turn slices/array refs into fixed-size array
  references via raw-pointer casts. No `build.rs`, no proc macros, no
  network / filesystem I/O, no `include_bytes!`, no obfuscation, no
  runtime dependencies (only `quickcheck` as dev-dep). Cargo.toml
  metadata is clean: BSD-2-Clause, repo at github.com/droundy/arrayref.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious): nothing found.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe w/o SAFETY): six `unsafe fn` / `unsafe { }` sites
  (lib.rs:61, 67, 112, 134, 144, 154, 209, 231, 241, 251, 287, 293).
  None has a `// SAFETY:` comment. The invariants are obvious to a
  reader (the surrounding macro guarantees the slice has the right
  length, either via a preceding `&arr[off..off+len]` bounds-check or
  via the const-sized `&[T; sum]` parameter type), but the convention
  is still absent. Caps the rating at `neutral`.
  
  Concern #3 (no miri): CI is `.github/workflows/rust.yml` running only
  `cargo build` + `cargo test` on ubuntu-latest. No miri, no clippy, no
  cross-platform. The unsafe is pure pointer arithmetic and would be
  miri-testable. Caps at `positive` on its own; combined with #2 the
  effective cap is `neutral`.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): walked each macro. In the `..` arms of
  `array_refs!` / `mut_array_refs!` the order is `let var_len = a.len()
  - MIN_LEN;` then `assert!(a.len() >= MIN_LEN)`. The subtraction
  underflows when the input is too small, but in debug builds the
  overflow check panics and in release builds `var_len` wraps and the
  following assert still fires before any UB occurs, so this is a code
  smell rather than a bug. `array_ref!` slices with `&$arr[offset..
  offset+$len]` first, so any OOB / overflow turns into a panic from
  slice indexing (overflowed `offset+len` wraps below `offset`, making
  start>end which panics). The non-`..` `array_refs!` / `mut_array_refs!`
  arms take `&[T; sum-of-lens]`, so the size is checked at compile time
  by the type system. The multiple-`&mut`-from-one-`&mut [T;N]` pattern
  in `mut_array_refs!` is the standard `split_at_mut`-style trick over
  non-overlapping ranges of a fresh `*mut`, which is sound. No
  reproducible bugs found.
