  source: https://crates.io
  name: backtrace
  version: 0.3.76
  revision: 775f6a1ba62e7d35a1fac76e64c61d9d4687b5f2
  digest: m82nvETcgk9vxltYWB0Mpu4LsBSi6P38lu7eHNRkICo
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: strong
comment: |-
  Reviewed every `.rs` file under `src/` (~7,800 LoC across 38 files) plus
  Cargo.toml, README, CI workflows. Maintained by The Rust Project Developers
  (rust-lang/backtrace-rs); this crate is used by std itself to print panic
  backtraces. License MIT OR Apache-2.0. No `build.rs` (`build = false`), no
  proc-macros. Deps are all standard ecosystem crates (cfg-if, rustc-demangle,
  addr2line, gimli, object, miniz_oxide, libc, windows-link; optional
  cpp_demangle, serde, ruzstd) — no typo-squats.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): nothing. No network I/O, no obfuscation,
  no `include_bytes!` blobs, no shell-outs. Filesystem reads are scoped to
  symbolication: opening the running executable / loaded shared libs for
  mmap, reading `/proc/self/maps` to identify the current exe, probing for
  `*.dSYM`, `.dwp`, `.gnu_debuglink`. All consistent with the stated purpose.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe without SAFETY): the crate has ~190 `unsafe` occurrences,
  largely unavoidable — FFI to libunwind/_Unwind_Backtrace, dbghelp, mmap,
  dlopen/dl_iterate_phdr, _dyld_*, loadquery, RtlVirtualUnwind. Most blocks
  have SAFETY comments or surrounding doc-comments explaining invariants;
  some FFI wrappers rely on the function-level "Safety" doc instead of a
  per-block `// SAFETY:` line, but the rationale is consistently stated.
  The `lock` module in `lib.rs` is explicitly documented as "partially
  unsound" with a candid explanation — it's crate-private and used in the
  documented pattern. The `Stash` arena in `symbolize/gimli/stash.rs` uses
  `UnsafeCell<Vec<Vec<u8>>>` with sound reasoning (inner `Vec<u8>` heap
  allocations are stable across outer-Vec reallocations).
  
  Concern #3 (miri): `.github/workflows/main.yml` runs a dedicated `miri` job:
  `MIRIFLAGS="-Zmiri-disable-isolation" cargo miri test`. There's also a
  Miri-specific backend (`backtrace/miri.rs`, `symbolize/miri.rs`) selected
  via `cfg(miri)` so the test suite exercises the non-FFI paths under miri.
  FFI paths (libunwind, dbghelp, dl_iterate_phdr) aren't miri-testable but
  that's a fundamental miri limitation, not a gap in the crate's hygiene.
  
  Concern #4 (functional correctness): no bugs found. Pointer arithmetic
  uses `wrapping_add`/`wrapping_sub` in the AVMA<->SVMA translation
  (`symbolize/gimli.rs::avma_to_svma`) with an explicit comment about
  overflow seen in the wild (issue #329). `parse_running_mmaps_unix.rs`
  has thorough unit tests for 32/64-bit `/proc/self/maps` parsing including
  paths with spaces. The `lru.rs` `MaybeUninit`-based LRU cache carefully
  maintains its `len` invariant. ELF/Mach-O/PE/XCOFF parsers all funnel
  malformed-input errors through `?` to `None`.
  
  Caveats: only inspected source statically (per project rules — no
  compilation, no test execution). Coverage breadth here trades off against
  per-block scrutiny of every `unsafe` SAFETY comment; spot-checked the
  high-traffic ones (libunwind callback, gimli mmap lifetime extension,
  Stash arena, Lru, libs_macos dyld walk, libs_dl_iterate_phdr callback).
