  digest: 3jz5rykbmt4FQH-kNVgQonhDWufVk74m8z0MC9rl7ag
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: unsafe-missing-safety-comment
  severity: low
  comment: |
    Two `unsafe` blocks (lib.rs:406, lib.rs:445) lack `// SAFETY:`
    comments. The reasoning is straightforward in both cases (see
    review comment) but should be documented at the call sites.
comment: |-
  Reviewed the full source: src/lib.rs (1681 lines incl. tests),
  Cargo.toml, README, benches/bench.rs, .github/workflows/rust.yml.
  No build.rs, no proc-macro, no_std-capable with a `std` default
  feature. Single first-party dep `bit-vec = 0.8.0`; optional serde
  derive support. Pure-Rust BitSet wrapper around `bit_vec::BitVec` —
  set ops (union/intersect/difference/symmetric_difference, both
  iterator and in-place forms), iteration, shrink_to_fit, truncate.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious): nothing suspicious. No I/O, no env reads,
  no include_bytes!, no Command, no FFI. Code descends from the
  long-removed std::collections::BitSet.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe SAFETY comments): two `unsafe` blocks, neither
  has a `// SAFETY:` comment — caps rating at `neutral`.
    - lib.rs:406-408 in other_op: writes back combined block via
      `storage_mut()[i] = new`. Safe in practice because
      self_bit_vec.len() >= other_bit_vec.len() after the grow above,
      and bitwise ops on the (zero-by-invariant) trailing bits
      preserve the trailing-zeros invariant for |, &, ^, &!.
    - lib.rs:445-448 in shrink_to_fit: truncates trailing all-zero
      blocks then set_len(trunc_len * B::bits()). Safe because the
      removed blocks were all zero, and rounding nbits up to a block
      boundary only "exposes" bits that were already zero.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): CI runs `cargo miri test` with
  `-Zmiri-strict-provenance` against both default and serde features.
  No additional cap.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): no bugs found. LSB-isolation trick in
  BlockIter::next (`head & (!head + 1)`) is the standard two's-
  complement idiom and is correct for any unsigned BitBlock.
  blocks_for_bits deliberately avoids usize::MAX overflow.
  Intersection::next's `n` cap equals min(self.nbits, other.nbits),
  a valid upper bound on intersection size.
