  digest: crjkZXLITOFFwnXnyz775eTKsFjkNHLOPE4U3mbptnE
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Small (~350 LOC) `no_std` block-buffer utility from RustCrypto, used as a
  building block for hash function implementations. Read every .rs file in
  src/ (lib.rs, sealed.rs) and tests/mod.rs. No build.rs, no proc-macros,
  single dependency on `generic-array = "0.14"`. License MIT OR Apache-2.0,
  repository link present and matches the cargo_vcs_info revision
  6d35952d3d3b124bc1049ad6fb406b42b1ce4bfe.
  
  Four `unsafe` blocks, all justified with `// SAFETY:` comments:
  - lib.rs:200 `unreachable_unchecked` inside `get_pos`. The invariant is
    upheld by every `set_pos_unchecked` call site (each is preceded by a
    bounds proof or invariant check). Sound.
  - lib.rs:348 `slice::from_raw_parts_mut` over `nb * N` bytes of a slice
    that was just split at `nb * N`. Alignment of `Block<N> = GenericArray<u8, N>`
    is 1, so the u8 -> Block<N> cast is fine. Sound.
  - sealed.rs:27 and sealed.rs:58 build a `(blocks, tail)` view over a slice
    via raw pointers. Traced the arithmetic for both Eager and Lazy variants
    (including the empty-input early return in Lazy and the `data.len() % N == 0`
    branch where `nb = len/N - 1`). All in-bounds. Sound.
  
  The `IsLess<U256>` / `Le<_,_>: NonZero` bounds keep `BlockSize < 256`, so
  `pos as u8` is always lossless (Eager pos in 0..BlockSize, Lazy in 0..=BlockSize,
  max 255). Zero `BlockSize` is rejected at runtime in `Default::default` and
  `try_new` — this is the soundness fix that motivated 0.10.4 (CHANGELOG cites
  PR #844).
  
  No miri job in the upstream CI workflow (.github/workflows/block-buffer.yml
  at the reviewed revision). The unsafe here is pure pointer/slice work, fully
  miri-testable, so per the rubric this caps the rating at `positive`.
  
  Tests in tests/mod.rs exercise both Eager and Lazy buffers across the
  padding/digest/set_data paths; no behavioural concerns surfaced from
  reading them. No grep hits for include_bytes!, process::Command, libc,
  network APIs, or other supply-chain red flags.
