review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: neutral
comment: |-
  Byte-string extension crate by BurntSushi (Andrew Gallant), author of memchr,
  regex, and ripgrep. Widely used, mature 1.X series. No build.rs (build = false
  in Cargo.toml), no proc-macros, no network or process spawning. Only embedded
  binary data is the precompiled regex-automata sparse DFAs under
  src/unicode/fsm/*.dfa (grapheme/word/sentence/whitespace break tables);
  these are loaded via the safe `DFA::from_bytes` API. No malicious or
  suspicious behavior observed.
  
  Read: lib.rs, bstr.rs, bstring.rs, ascii.rs, byteset/{mod,scalar}.rs,
  escape_bytes.rs, ext_slice.rs (main code paths plus iterators and the
  SAFETY-bearing blocks), ext_vec.rs (insert_str + conversion paths),
  utf8.rs, io.rs, unicode/{mod,grapheme,fsm/mod,fsm/grapheme_break_fwd}.rs.
  Scanned the rest with Grep for unsafe / process / Command / libc / network
  APIs — clean.
  
  Unsafe usage falls into three buckets:
  1. Casts between &[u8] and &BStr (bstr.rs:73,78,84,90). Sound because
     `#[repr(transparent)] struct BStr { bytes: [u8] }`, but the unsafe
     blocks lack explicit `// SAFETY:` comments.
  2. `str::from_utf8_unchecked` after `utf8::validate` succeeds. These have
     proper `// SAFETY:` comments in ext_slice.rs / ext_vec.rs / utf8.rs.
  3. Pointer-arithmetic SIMD/scalar fast paths in ascii.rs and
     byteset/scalar.rs. The `unsafe { ... }` blocks wrap whole function
     bodies (ascii.rs:62, 129; byteset/scalar.rs:28, 67) and contain only
     `debug_assert!`s rather than `// SAFETY:` justifications. Invariants
     are defensible (length checks before pointer-add, alignment-mask
     adjustments) but not stated in canonical form.
  
  Per the SAFETY-comment rule, this caps the rating at `neutral`.
  
  Miri: the crate is miri-aware — `#[cfg(miri)]` flips the x86_64 SIMD
  path to a scalar fallback and dials down quickcheck/test ranges so miri
  runs are tractable. However the upstream `.github/workflows/ci.yml`
  (verified at the published vcs sha 8904072067) has the `miri:` job
  commented out, so miri is not actually run in CI on this release. The
  unsafe in ascii.rs and byteset/scalar.rs is pure-Rust pointer arithmetic
  and would be miri-testable. This further supports the `neutral` cap.
  
  Functional correctness: no reproducible bugs found. UTF-8 decoder is a
  textbook Hoehrmann DFA; Split / Lines / LinesWithTerminator iterators
  look correct; insert_str's ptr::copy is guarded by a `reserve(bytes.len())`
  so the destination range is in-bounds.
  
  Dependencies: memchr, regex-automata (both BurntSushi), optional serde.
  License MIT OR Apache-2.0.
