  Patch release over 1.12.0 (which I reviewed previously). Diff vs 1.12.0
  is minuscule: src/lib.rs swaps the docs.rs nightly feature attr from
  `doc_auto_cfg` to `doc_cfg`; src/ext_slice.rs adds an explicit `'_`
  lifetime on a `Cow<OsStr>` return and tweaks one doc-comment link to
  `[BString](crate::BString)`. Cargo.toml is just the version bump. The
  precompiled regex-automata DFAs under src/unicode/fsm/*.dfa are
  byte-identical to 1.12.0 (verified with `diff -rq`). No new code paths,
  no new dependencies, no new unsafe. Cargo.lock dev-dep bumps don't
  affect consumers.
  
  Carrying forward findings from the 1.12.0 review:
  
  Byte-string extension crate by BurntSushi (Andrew Gallant), author of
  memchr, regex, and ripgrep. No build.rs (build = false in Cargo.toml),
  no proc-macros, no network or process spawning. Embedded binary data
  is limited to the precompiled regex-automata sparse DFAs under
  src/unicode/fsm/*.dfa loaded via the safe `DFA::from_bytes` API. No
  malicious or suspicious behavior observed.
  
  Unsafe usage falls into three buckets:
  1. Casts between &[u8] and &BStr (bstr.rs:73,78,84,90). Sound because
     `#[repr(transparent)] struct BStr { bytes: [u8] }`, but the unsafe
     blocks lack explicit `// SAFETY:` comments.
  2. `str::from_utf8_unchecked` after `utf8::validate` succeeds. These
     have proper `// SAFETY:` comments in ext_slice.rs / ext_vec.rs /
     utf8.rs.
  3. Pointer-arithmetic SIMD/scalar fast paths in ascii.rs and
     byteset/scalar.rs. The `unsafe { ... }` blocks wrap whole function
     bodies (ascii.rs:62,129; byteset/scalar.rs:28,67) and contain only
     `debug_assert!`s rather than `// SAFETY:` justifications.
     Invariants are defensible but not stated in canonical form.
  
  Per the SAFETY-comment rule, this caps the rating at `neutral`.
  
  Miri: crate is miri-aware (`#[cfg(miri)]` swaps SIMD for scalar and
  shrinks quickcheck ranges) but the upstream `.github/workflows/ci.yml`
  miri job is still commented out at the 1.12.1 vcs sha. The unsafe in
  ascii.rs and byteset/scalar.rs is pure-Rust pointer arithmetic and
  would be miri-testable. Supports the `neutral` cap.
  
  Functional correctness: no reproducible bugs found. UTF-8 decoder is
  a Hoehrmann DFA; Split / Lines / LinesWithTerminator iterators look
  correct; insert_str's ptr::copy is guarded by `reserve(bytes.len())`.
  
  Dependencies unchanged: memchr, regex-automata (both BurntSushi),
  optional serde. License MIT OR Apache-2.0.
