  necessity — it implements a bump arena. lib.rs has ~65 `unsafe`
  occurrences, raw_vec.rs ~17, vec.rs ~64, string.rs ~35. SAFETY
  documentation is uneven: well-reasoned in newer code (e.g.
  alloc_try_with at lib.rs:1199-1259 explains why ptr::read of the Err is
  sound; Box impls at boxed.rs:589-603, 697-700 give crisp justifications;
  EmptyChunkFooter at lib.rs:332-353 explains the Sync), but the
  std-library forks under `collections/` rely on inherited per-function
  contracts rather than per-block SAFETY tags. None of the unsafe I
  inspected has demonstrably wrong reasoning; debug_assert! invariants
  (alignment, range, capacity) are dense and consistent with the prose.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): the unsafe is miri-testable (raw-pointer arithmetic,
  transmute, lifetime extension; no FFI/syscalls/asm). I could not verify
  miri-in-CI from the packaged crate because `.github/*` is excluded.
  Upstream is known to run miri, but I am not relying on that here.
  Treating this as "unsafe, no verified miri" → cap at positive per the
  rubric.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): overflow handling is explicit (round_up_to
  returns Option, checked_add/checked_mul throughout, alloc_guard for
  32-bit isize::MAX). The fast-path allocator at try_alloc_layout_fast
  (lib.rs:1888-1981) uses wrapping_sub safely guarded by capacity
  comparisons. The shrink path at lib.rs:2284-2334 includes a careful
  comment explaining why `(old_size + 1) / 2` (round-up division) is
  required to avoid overlapping copy_nonoverlapping. The
  alloc_try_with rewind logic is subtle but reasoned through correctly
  (last-allocation check, single-allocation-in-chunk argument). I did
  not find a reproducible bug.
  
  3.20.2 specifically restores `Send`/`Sync` impls for `Box<'_, T: ?Sized>`
  at boxed.rs:697,700 — justification is correct (Box has exclusive
  ownership of T).
