review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Bump allocator arena by Nick Fitzgerald (fitzgen). MIT/Apache-2.0,
  https://github.com/fitzgen/bumpalo. Diff vs 3.20.2 is small and
  targeted at two changelog-noted fixes.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious code): no build.rs, no proc-macros, no
  include_bytes!, no process/network/FS APIs. Dependencies unchanged
  (optional serde, allocator-api2). Cargo.toml still excludes
  /.github/*, /benches, /tests from the package, so I could not inspect
  miri-in-CI directly. Nothing suspicious in the published source.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe without SAFETY): new RewindGuard at lib.rs:62-161
  has a thorough /// # Safety block on `new` (lib.rs:82-95) naming all
  four invariants the caller must uphold; the Drop impl explains the
  same-chunk vs. new-chunk reclamation reasoning inline (lib.rs:124-158).
  Call sites in alloc_slice_(try_)fill_with at lib.rs:1547-1665 wrap
  ptr::write loops in the standard one-unsafe-block-per-function pattern
  bumpalo uses elsewhere. Reworked DrainFilter::drop (collections/vec.rs:
  2955-3008) ports std's BackshiftOnDrop guard pattern; no per-block
  SAFETY comments but the operations are bounds-respecting slice writes
  consistent with the rest of the file.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): unsafe remains miri-testable (raw pointer math, no
  FFI/syscalls/asm). Cannot verify miri-in-CI from packaged crate (per
  #1). Upstream is known to run miri but I am not relying on that here;
  cap at positive per the rubric.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): the changelog fixes look right.
  - RewindGuard correctly reclaims the bump pointer only when the
    guarded allocation is still the most-recent one (is_last_allocation
    check at lib.rs:120); if `f` itself allocated inside the bump,
    rewind is skipped and memory leaks rather than corrupting an
    interleaved allocation. The new-chunk branch (lib.rs:136-157)
    correctly resets to round_mut_ptr_down_to(footer, MIN_ALIGN), which
    matches new_chunk's initial ptr setup (lib.rs:1010).
  - DrainFilter's new Drop creates BackshiftOnDrop *before* calling
    `self.pred` so a predicate panic mid-iteration leaves the vec in a
    valid state (collections/vec.rs:2982-2987). guard.idx is bumped
    *after* pred returns but *before* drop_in_place, so a panicking
    drop also leaves the bookkeeping consistent.
  No reproducible bug found.
