    `neutral`. bytes_mut.rs is better but still incomplete.
comment: |-
  Reviewed crate published at version 1.11.1 by Carl Lerche and Sean
  McArthur (tokio-rs). De-facto byte-buffer library in the async/
  networking Rust ecosystem (hyper, tonic, h2, prost, axum, all of
  tokio downstream). Read every .rs file under src/ (lib.rs, bytes.rs,
  bytes_mut.rs, serde.rs, loom.rs, fmt/mod.rs, fmt/debug.rs, fmt/hex.rs,
  buf/{mod,buf_impl,buf_mut,chain,iter,limit,reader,take,uninit_slice,
  vec_deque,writer}.rs), Cargo.toml, README.md, CHANGELOG.md,
  .github/workflows/ci.yml, ci/{miri,tsan,panic-abort,test-stable}.sh.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): no build.rs (`build = false` in
  Cargo.toml line 21), no proc-macro, no `include_bytes!`, no
  `Command`/syscall/network APIs, no obfuscation. Only optional deps
  are portable-atomic (gated `extra-platforms` feature for targets
  without atomic CAS) and serde (gated `serde` feature). License MIT,
  repo https://github.com/tokio-rs/bytes, authors well-known. No red
  flags.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): heavy unsafe in bytes.rs and
  bytes_mut.rs implementing a vtable-based shared-storage scheme with
  pointer tagging (KIND_ARC/KIND_VEC LSB, original-capacity bits,
  vec-position bits). The design is sound and well-known. However
  `// SAFETY:` comments are sparse: bytes.rs has none, bytes_mut.rs
  has ~8 across ~50 unsafe occurrences. The `unsafe fn` definitions
  carry `# Safety` rustdoc, but per the rubric every unsafe *block*
  should be commented, so this caps rating at `neutral`. See issue.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): yes — .github/workflows/ci.yml runs a dedicated
  miri job invoking ci/miri.sh, which runs `cargo miri test` with
  `MIRIFLAGS=-Zmiri-strict-provenance`, on host plus
  `mips64-unknown-linux-gnuabi64` (big-endian coverage), plus a
  release build (wrapping overflow). CI also runs loom (`--cfg loom`)
  for concurrency model checking, tsan/asan, panic=abort tests, and
  matrix builds across i686/armv7/powerpc/powerpc64/wasm32-wasip1.
  This is among the strongest test coverage in the ecosystem for an
  unsafe-heavy crate. No additional cap from §3.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): 1.11.1 ships a single fix vs 1.11.0 —
  "Fix integer overflow in BytesMut::reserve". The current
  reserve_inner (bytes_mut.rs:607-787) uses `checked_add` for both
  `len + additional` (line 678) and `new_cap + offset` (line 698),
  panicking explicitly on overflow rather than wrapping. Refcount
  overflow is guarded in shallow_clone_arc (bytes.rs:1466),
  owned_clone (bytes.rs:1126), and increment_shared
  (bytes_mut.rs:1448), each comparing against `usize::MAX >> 1` /
  `isize::MAX as usize` and calling `crate::abort()` on overflow.
  release_shared uses the canonical Acquire-load-after-Release-fetch_sub
  Arc drop dance (with a load instead of fence per the documented tsan
  workaround). shallow_clone_vec's compare_exchange promotion (Vec→Arc)
  initializes the new refcount to 2 (self + clone) and on Err releases
  the new Box without dropping the moved-out Vec via `mem::forget` —
  correct. slice() and slice_ref() bounds-check with `checked_add`/
  asserts before pointer arithmetic. No off-by-one, no panic on
  plausible inputs, no concurrency bug spotted in the vtable
  dispatch paths.
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project rules.
