review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Serde CBOR (de)serializer, sibling of ciborium-io / ciborium-ll. Read every
  .rs file under src/, Cargo.toml, README, and skimmed tests/.
  
  Concern 1 (malicious/suspicious): nothing found. No build.rs, no proc-macro
  (`cbor!` is a declarative macro), no `include_bytes!`/`include_str!`, no
  `std::process`, `Command`, network or filesystem APIs, no `env!`/`option_env!`,
  no `#[no_mangle]`, no inline asm. Dependencies are the author's own
  ciborium-io/ciborium-ll plus serde. License Apache-2.0, repo metadata
  matches enarx/ciborium.
  
  Concern 2 (`unsafe` without SAFETY): the library code contains zero `unsafe`
  blocks/fns. Grep finds `unsafe` only in tests/fuzz.rs (fork()/pipe()/waitpid()
  libc bindings for a fuzz harness), which is not shipped to consumers. N/A.
  
  Concern 3 (`unsafe` without miri): N/A - no library unsafe.
  
  Concern 4 (correctness): no bugs found that I can reproduce. Notes:
  - Decoder enforces a default recursion limit of 256 (src/de/mod.rs:847);
    tests/recursion.rs proves indefinite-length arrays, maps, bytes, and
    text all terminate without stack overflow.
  - Bigint decoding (src/de/mod.rs:90-117) bounds the accumulator to 16
    bytes and rejects longer inputs with "bigint too large"; round-trips
    u128::MAX and i128::MIN correctly.
  - `unwrap()` calls in src/ are guarded: `chars().next().unwrap()` follows
    a `chars().count() == 1` check (de/mod.rs:308, value/de.rs:336);
    `next().unwrap()` in MapAccess::next_value_seed runs after a successful
    peek in next_key_seed (value/de.rs:544); `temp.take().unwrap()` follows
    the paired serialize_key (value/ser.rs:375); `parent.take().unwrap()`
    in newtype_variant_seed consumes `self` so cannot be reentered
    (tag.rs:165). `unreachable!()` in Value's Integer dispatch
    (value/de.rs:249, value/ser.rs:56) is only reachable if a value of
    type Integer (internal i128) doesn't fit in i128 - impossible.
  - Map(Some(n))'s `size_hint()` is forwarded verbatim from the wire, so
    a pathological encoder can claim a huge length; mitigated upstream by
    serde's own capacity guards in Vec/HashMap deserializers. Worth being
    aware of but not a ciborium bug.
  
  The `cbor!` macro and tag handling use the sentinel names "@@TAG@@",
  "@@TAGGED@@", "@@UNTAGGED@@"; a user type literally named "@@TAG@@"
  would interact oddly with tag dispatch, but this is a documented design,
  not a bug. `serialized_canonical_cmp` (value/canonical.rs:9) discards
  the serialize error with `let _ =`; serializing an in-memory Value to a
  Vec<u8> cannot fail in practice.
----- SIGN CREV PROOF -----
