package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: ciborium-ll
  version: 0.2.2
  revision: fdf3ec5c53256000f8e12f06c361ca18026a8d99
  digest: i5sWXmAHgwLI3UongdEp9oTMatH2iBBDdP2gYwF-B-8
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Low-level CBOR header codec, sibling of the already-reviewed
  ciborium-io / ciborium 0.2.2. Read every .rs file under src/
  (lib.rs, hdr.rs, dec.rs, enc.rs, seg.rs — ~1100 lines including
  tests), Cargo.toml(.orig), README.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): clean. No build.rs, no
  proc-macro, no `include_bytes!`/`include_str!`, no
  `std::process`/`Command`, no `libc`/FFI, no network or filesystem
  APIs, no `env!`/`option_env!`, no `#[no_mangle]`, no inline asm,
  no `transmute`. Crate is `#![cfg_attr(not(feature = "std"),
  no_std)]` with `#![deny(missing_docs)]`, `#![deny(clippy::all)]`,
  `#![deny(clippy::cargo)]`. Dependencies are minimal and
  appropriate: ciborium-io 0.2.2 (sibling), half 2.2 (well-known
  IEEE 754 f16), and hex 0.4 (dev-only). License Apache-2.0,
  repository link matches enarx/ciborium.
  
  Concern #2 (`unsafe` without SAFETY): N/A — grep for `unsafe`
  across the crate returns zero matches. No `unsafe` blocks, no
  `unsafe fn`, no `unsafe impl`.
  
  Concern #3 (`unsafe` without miri): N/A — no unsafe code.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): no reproducible bugs found. Walked the
  state machine in dec.rs / enc.rs / hdr.rs / seg.rs.
  - `pull_title` (dec.rs:62) reads major from `prefix[0] >> 5`
    (3 bits → exhaustive 0..=7 plus `unreachable!()`), and minor
    from `prefix[0] & 0x1f`: 0..=23 → `This`, 24..=27 → `Next1..
    Next8`, 31 → `More`, reserved 28/29/30 → `Error::Syntax`.
    Matches RFC 7049 §2.1.
  - `Title -> Header` (hdr.rs:78) routes lengths through
    `usize::try_from`, so a u64 length that doesn't fit usize on
    32-bit targets becomes `InvalidError` rather than truncating.
    Indefinite-length (`Minor::More`) is rejected for Positive /
    Negative / Tag (`int()` returns None → InvalidError), accepted
    for Bytes/Text/Array/Map (length = None), and produces
    `Header::Break` only under `Major::Other`. Spec-correct.
  - The `push_title` / `pull_title` buffer (dec.rs:98) shaves
    `title.minor.as_ref().len() + 1` from `offset` on push and
    adds the same amount back on pull, so the offset is restored
    correctly even when the synthesized canonical minor encoding
    differs from the non-canonical wire bytes that were originally
    read. Offset becomes transiently inconsistent between push and
    pull (off by `actual_minor_len - canonical_minor_len`), but
    `Segments::new` always immediately pulls, and the final
    post-pull offset matches the real wire position. No bug.
  - `Segment::pull` (seg.rs:131) handles the saved-bytes prefix
    via `let next = &mut full[min(size, prev)..];` and updates
    `unread` by the size of `next`, never by the full slice. If
    the caller's buffer is `<= saved_len` so `size <= prev`, the
    Text parser early-returns "" and no read occurs — a documented
    precondition, gracefully handled rather than misbehaving.
  - `Encoder::text` (enc.rs:99) enforces a minimum chunk of 4
    bytes — the longest UTF-8 code point — guaranteeing the inner
    `while len > 0 && from_utf8(...).is_err()` loop always finds
    a valid prefix of length ≥ 1 and forward progress is made
    (no infinite loop on valid input).
  - `Encoder::bytes` (enc.rs:66) enforces a minimum chunk of 1,
    so `chunks(max)` is well-defined.
  - Float encoding (hdr.rs:146) tries f16 → f32 → f64 by
    bit-exact round-trip (`to_bits()` equality). Non-canonical
    NaNs that don't round-trip cleanly fall through to f64, which
    is conservative-but-correct.
  
  Lenient-parsing notes (not bugs; RFC 7049 §3.2 leaves strictness
  to the consumer): the decoder accepts non-canonical length
  encodings (e.g., positive 10 encoded in 8 bytes) and accepts
  simple values 0..=31 in the 2-byte `0xf8 xx` form even though
  values <32 must use the 1-byte form for canonical CBOR. The
  encoder always emits canonical lengths and uses the 1-byte
  form for simple ≤23, but does not reject reserved simple
  values 24..=31. The crate is documented as "low-level";
  strictness is delegated to higher layers (ciborium).
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project
  rules.
----- SIGN CREV PROOF -----
